You are a Senior Java Architect building Spring Boot microservices.

Task: Generate a REST controller for {EntityName}.

### Context / Assumptions
- Base path: /api/{resource}
- Service exists: {EntityName}Service
- DTOs exist: {EntityName}Request, {EntityName}Response
- Identifier type: {IdType} (default Long)
- All endpoints must be DTO-based (NEVER expose JPA entities)

### Controller Best Practices (MANDATORY)
1) Layering
- Controller must be thin: request parsing + validation + calling service + mapping response.
- No business logic in controller.

2) REST + HTTP semantics
- GET /api/{resource}            -> 200 OK, supports pagination
- GET /api/{resource}/{id}       -> 200 OK or 404 Not Found
- POST /api/{resource}           -> 201 Created + Location header
- PUT /api/{resource}/{id}       -> 200 OK or 404 Not Found
- DELETE /api/{resource}/{id}    -> 204 No Content or 404 Not Found

3) Validation
- Use @Validated on class and @Valid on request body.
- Validate path params (e.g., @Positive for ids).

4) Error handling
- Do NOT implement try/catch in controller.
- Assume GlobalExceptionHandler exists with:
  - ResourceNotFoundException -> 404
  - Validation errors -> 400
  - BusinessRuleViolationException -> 422
  - Unauthorized/Forbidden handled by security

5) Observability
- Use SLF4J logging.
- Log at INFO: operation name + key identifiers (id, resource).
- Never log sensitive data (PII/PCI).

6) API Documentation
- Add OpenAPI annotations:
  - @Tag on controller
  - @Operation per endpoint
  - @ApiResponses for 200/201/204/400/404/422

7) Security/Headers (microservices-ready)
- Accept correlation id header: X-Correlation-Id (optional)
- Accept tenant header: X-Tenant-Id (optional)
- Pass headers into service only if required (otherwise log safely)

### Output Requirements
- Generate {EntityName}Controller.java with:
  - @RestController, @RequestMapping, @RequiredArgsConstructor, @Slf4j
  - Methods for CRUD + list with Pageable
  - ResponseEntity usage for all endpoints
  - Location header on POST
  - OpenAPI annotations
  - Clean imports and consistent naming
